04087nam a22006135i 9780691236902DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212007nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912369027 a10.1515/97806912369022doi  a(DE-B1597)600740  a(OCoLC)1269268794  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDP302.V205bU55 2007eb 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a946/.762221 aBurns, Robert Ignatius, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiplomatarium of the Crusader Kingdom of Valencia :bThe Registered Charters of Its Conqueror, Jaume I, 1257-1276. IV: Unifying Crusader Valencia, The Central Years of Jaume the Conqueror /cRobert Ignatius Burns. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (600 p.) :b7 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tPREFACE -- tCOMMON SIGLA IN TEXT AND NOTES -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCharters 1000-1001 -- tCharters 1101-1200 -- tCharters 1201-1300 -- tYears 1270-1273 -- tYear 1271 -- tYear 1272 -- tYear 1273 -- tCharters 1301-1400 -- tCharters 1401-15000 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis fourth volume in Robert Burns's celebrated series on the warrior King Jaume the Conqueror's Kingdom of Valencia describes the crucial years of 1270 to 1273, a period during which Jaume continued his consolidation of political power for future territorial expansion. Here in the colonial kingdom that he carved out from the Islamic Mediterranean regions of coastal Spain, Jaume presided over a society more complex than any in Christendom. This lively frontier was home to semiautonomous communities of Muslims, Jews, and Christian settlers. Jaume's pioneering exploitation of Valencia's Islamic paper mills left behind thousands of charters--records in the king's registers--that provide a wealth of detailed information about every aspect of these parallel cultures. Burns's Diplomatarium volumes represent the first systematic exploration of this massive deployment of paper in the West. They open up to readers the rich humanistic panorama of medieval life as seen from the traveling court of a conqueror king. The 500 charters collected in this book cover a kaleidoscope of topics, including public baths, castles, the renaissance of law, irrigation, mosques and monasteries, hospitals and banks, even exotic women. There are records on crossbow manufacture, riot and fire control, ship launchers, dogs of war, crime, slavery, prisons, and pardons. This critical edition includes reconstructions of each charter in its original Latin or Romance language with a corresponding translation in English, making it invaluable for students and scholars alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691236902zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691236902423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691236902/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK